On 15 Aug, Charles Hines wrote:

> Now I could be wrong, which happens occasionally ;^).  So if someone
> provides me with actual evidence that the the hashtable provides a
> major benefit over the binary search, I'll consider changing it.

The major benefit of a hash table over a binary search is that lookups
using a "perfect" hash table are constant (one lookup).  A binary
search algorithm on a sorted table takes an average of log2(n)
lookups.  Thus, for fast lookup, hash tables win.

On a more practical note, with only 80-100 items in the table, lookup
times may not be too much of an issue, especially when running on a
500 Mhz Alpha system [smile!].

In addition, somebody on this list also indicated that people without
access to gperf may not be able to compile fvwm2.  My answer to that is
it should be simple enough to include the gperf output as well as the
input in the fvwm2 distribution.  One would only need gperf if one was
going to extend the command table.

I don't have the free time right now to acutally implement gperf in
fvwm2, so I would like to keep it as a suggestion for possible
improvement and not as a practical necessity for fvwm2.0.46.

