Unfortunately, the animations are pretty tightly bound to the rewritten
menu code.  The problem is that the menu code (before my rewrite) limits
the number of levels deep to 3 -- it only remembers the previous menu,
the current menu, and the next menu in scalar pointers (i.e., not in an
array).  To make matters worse, the notion of what the current menu is
varies between the menu styles (mwm style has different semantics from
fvwm style, etc.).  The animations require reliable navigation of
greater depth so that intermediate menus can be animated back to the
right as the user unwinds to higher level menus.

If the current menu code were robust, I'd agree about not changing
stuff;  however it's *buggy* big time!  And the bugs are often due to
various major design flaws, and cannot be corrected individually (I
tried; I didn't want to rewrite as much of the menu code as I had to,
but the more I understood what was going on, the uglier it all looked).

