My guess is that a good speedup could be gotten by remembering the last
command dispatched and prechecking for that w/ a strcmp and go right away
(avoiding the binary/linear scan of the command table) if it's the
same.  This is a primitive dynamic version of the obvious idea to do a
linear search w/ the most frequently used commands at the head of the
list.  My claim is that the most frequently used command is the prior
command (i.e., commands are often repeated; e.g., a "AddToMenu" section
might have hundreds of such commands all in a row).  [This is especially
true when aggressively using m4 to preprocess the fvwm2rc files like
TheNextLevel does].

Another reason that now is the time for the menu patch is that it'll be
easier to apply now (it applies cleanly to 2.0.45, and the further away
we get from that, the more work it'll be to get the changes back in the code).

