"Charles Hines" <chuck_hines@VNET.IBM.COM> writes:

> Larry> Thus, for fast lookup, hash tables win.
> 
> I never denied that.  It was the relative benefit vs complexity that I
> was arguing.

Development effort is minimal, since it's already done.  As Larry
suggested, using a prepackaged gperf output for those w/o gperf
eliminates that as a concern.

> BTW - the 'actual' evidence I had in mind was something along the
> lines of a table comparing the actual startup times for the two
> different implementations for a sampling of different startup scripts.

As mentioned in my patch description, the hash table reduced my startup
time by 15% or so in 2.0.45 on my rather lengthy .fvwm2rc (about 100k after
FvwmM4 processing).  Note, too, that since I do use FvwmM4, that
accounts for a bigger chunk of startup time than others would
experience.  Said another way, I'd expect better than 15% improvement
for those who write pure .fvwm2rc, not using FvwmM4 (or FvwmCpp for that
matter [though why would you do that???]).

> Larry> On a more practical note, with only 80-100 items in the table, lookup
> Larry> times may not be too much of an issue,
> 
> That was part of the point I was trying to make - worst case is 7
> compares for 65-128 items, many of which will move on after checking
> only 1 character.  That shouldn't take very long at all, especially

It's the function calls that takes time, not the compare.  The fact that
"strcmp" can short-circuit the compare after 1 character doesn't change
the running time much (besides, a lot of commonly used commands share
prefixes, anyway).

Bottom line, it empirically does make a difference, and makes more of a
difference as more commands are added, and is already written, and isn't
much more work and adds only a little bit of complexity (mostly to the
build procedure--it actually simplifies the code quite a bit;  a binary
search is a lot easier to get wrong than a simple hash table lookup).

I vote for using the hash table implementation as an option for now, and
later remove the complexity of the alternative methods if there are no problems.

