In message <9708181330.AA31194@quarry.zk3.dec.com>, Larry Gensch writes:
[...hash tables vs. bin search...]
>The major benefit of a hash table over a binary search is that lookups
>using a "perfect" hash table are constant (one lookup).  A binary
>search algorithm on a sorted table takes an average of log2(n)
>lookups.  Thus, for fast lookup, hash tables win.
>
>On a more practical note, with only 80-100 items in the table, lookup
>times may not be too much of an issue, especially when running on a
>500 Mhz Alpha system [smile!].

Note: one "perfect" hash lookup is O(1) memory reference, one binary
tree lookup is O(log N) memory references.  The memory system on
the 500Mhz Alpha is a *lot* slower then anything else (except I/O)
on that Alpha.

So the speed diffrence between the "perfect" hash and a bin lookup
is likely to be more then you expect on faster CPUs!

>In addition, somebody on this list also indicated that people without
>access to gperf may not be able to compile fvwm2.  My answer to that is
>it should be simple enough to include the gperf output as well as the
>input in the fvwm2 distribution.  One would only need gperf if one was
>going to extend the command table.

They do this sort of thing with the perl distribution, you need bison
(or flex and bison?) to add new keywords to perl, but you don't need
them to just compile perl.

A similar thing is done with the xtank distribution.

If you are careful with the make targets (i.e. make clean doesn't
remove your ability to re-build) nobody complains.  If you are
careless folks complain...

