Well, here's my use of animated moves of windows.  I, in fact, do use
opaque windows, and much prefer the way the CSM-f keystroke lets my eyes
know what has happened to the window by moving it to the top left corner
with animation, rather than just having the window jump there w/o visual
cues.  To be complete, the framed move should do the animation, too (I'm
pretty sure I don't support that);  to me it's a question of visual
feedback that even a low-resources machine might benefit from.

However, the one very important thing missing from AnimatedMove is a
flag that toggles whether the pointer moves with the move or not.  i.e.,
you can imagine moving the pointer an equivalent distance so that the
pointer stays in the same position relative to the window.  This is good
behaviour if you are moving the current window.  BUT, if you are moving
another window, moving the pointer is a big mistake (it'd go off
screen).  There should be an argument that lets you say
"MovePointerToo", "NoMovePointer", or "Automatic" (the default) which
would only move the pointer when invoked on the current window (is this testable)?

# FixWindowSize is really nice on a small screen,
# when you get a window way too big-- this makes
# it 85% of the screen by 85% of the screen, and puts
# it in the top left
AddToFunc FixWindowSize
+ "I" Resize 85 85
+ "I" AnimatedMove 0p 0p

Key f 		A	CSM	FixWindowSize

