"Charles Hines" <chuck_hines@VNET.IBM.COM> writes:

> This brings up another thought - specify the hotkey in the new section
> too?  Then we wouldn't have to worry about any special chars in the
> string at all, the hotkey could be a character that isn't in the
> string at all (making the builtin winlist generation slightly easier),
> and the hotkey could be universally placed at the beginning of the
> menu entry instead of highlighting it in the string.  Or allow both
> ways?  Thoughts?

You could allow specifying it via a <> option, and if it is, then make
that be a letter in front of the menu item.  Using the current method
could mean underline it -- that way the user can use either method (or
mix them) w/o adding a new menu style.

The big things I care about are *at least* warning when a shortcut key
is used repetitive times and splitting long menus into multiple menus.
Ideally, we could have a mechanism to say "automatically" pick a
shortcut key.  My TheNextLevel does this w/ preprocessing, but breaks
when you are dealing w/ long menus that get split since at the FvwmM4
level, it still thinks of the menu items as belonging to the same
super-long menu and won't reuse shortcut keys.  Fvwm can and should be
smarter.  The complication is that you can't assign the shortcut key
until after the whole menu is created (i.e., not until when the menus
get built internally).  Consider

"Foo" <AutoShortcut> Function Foo
"Bar &foo" Function Bar

Here I think that the Bar item should get the F shortcut, but the
obvious algorithm for the auto shortcuts would have already assigned
that shortcut to do the Foo shortcut.  Because of the dynamic way menus
are created, you need to defer selection of auto shortcuts until later.

