>>>>> "Greg" == Greg Badros <gjb@cs.washington.edu> writes:

Greg> "Charles Hines" <chuck_hines@VNET.IBM.COM> writes:

Larry> Thus, for fast lookup, hash tables win.

>> I never denied that.  It was the relative benefit vs complexity that I
>> was arguing.

Greg> Development effort is minimal, since it's already done.  As Larry
Greg> suggested, using a prepackaged gperf output for those w/o gperf
Greg> eliminates that as a concern.

The complexity arises in adding things in the future (either by myself
or by those submitting patches affecting the function list).  Plus in
the readablilty of the source code.

>> BTW - the 'actual' evidence I had in mind was something along the
>> lines of a table comparing the actual startup times for the two
>> different implementations for a sampling of different startup scripts.

Greg> As mentioned in my patch description, the hash table reduced my
Greg> startup time by 15% or so in 2.0.45 on my rather lengthy
Greg> .fvwm2rc (about 100k after FvwmM4 processing).  Note, too, that
Greg> since I do use FvwmM4, that accounts for a bigger chunk of
Greg> startup time than others would experience.  Said another way,
Greg> I'd expect better than 15% improvement for those who write pure
Greg> .fvwm2rc, not using FvwmM4 (or FvwmCpp for that matter [though
Greg> why would you do that???]).

Ok, but that is over the original linear search.  I'd still be willing
to bet that the binary search provides very close to that same
improvement amount.  But then, perhaps not - I haven't had a chance to
do any actual timed comparison yet (and no one else has offered one
either).

Larry> On a more practical note, with only 80-100 items in the table, lookup
Larry> times may not be too much of an issue,
>>
>> That was part of the point I was trying to make - worst case is 7
>> compares for 65-128 items, many of which will move on after checking
>> only 1 character.  That shouldn't take very long at all, especially

Greg> It's the function calls that takes time, not the compare.  The fact that
Greg> "strcmp" can short-circuit the compare after 1 character doesn't change
Greg> the running time much

Ok, I'll give you that.  But it would probably be pretty easy for me
to implement that binary search inline instead of using the bsearch &
compare function approach, eliminating most/all of the extra function
calls.  And it would still be rather simple code.

Greg> (besides, a lot of commonly used commands share prefixes, anyway).

True, but the only real significant ones are currently Add[To]* and
Window*.  Putting in your last command precheck idea will probably
help a bit to get around that problem as well.

Greg> Bottom line, it empirically does make a difference, and makes
Greg> more of a difference as more commands are added,

Both very true.

Greg> and is already written, and isn't much more work and adds only a
Greg> little bit of complexity (mostly to the build procedure--

Which means it mostly inconviences me. :)  And any patch submitters, of
course.  Perhaps this makes me a little biased?

Greg> it actually simplifies the code quite a bit; a binary search is a
Greg> lot easier to get wrong than a simple hash table lookup).

True - I do have to make sure that I keep the table in proper ascii
order (ignoring case).  But that isn't too difficult most days... :)

Greg> I vote for using the hash table implementation as an option for
Greg> now, and later remove the complexity of the alternative methods
Greg> if there are no problems.

Sorry, I'm not trying to be a pain in the ass about this, but I really
don't want to add it right now - for all the reasons I've already
stated: I think the simple binary search (especially with the
additional last command precheck you suggested) should provide a more
than adequete speedup (admittedly less than the hash table) without
really adding complexity to any portion of the code or build process.

Perhaps I'm wrong, but no one has changed my mind yet (and I can be a
little stubborn at times - ask my wife). :)

Chuck

